eq 0$. Without loss % of generality, say $c_{1}
eq 0$. Then \@@amsalign$\displaystyle c_{1}\vec{v}_{1}$&$\displaystyle=-c_{2}\vec{v}_{2}-% \dots-c_{k}\vec{v}_{k}$\ $\displaystyle\vec{v}_{1}$&$\displaystyle=- rac{c_{2}}{c_{1}}\vec{v}_{2}-% \dots- rac{c_{k}}{c_{1}}\vec{v}_{k}$ The righthand side of this equation should remind us of the span. In this case% , of $	ext{Span}\left\{\vec{v}_{2},\dots,\vec{v}_{k}ight\}$. That is, $\vec% {v}_{1}$ lies in the span of the other $\vec{v}_{i}$'s. } \end{enumerate} \par \@@section{section}{Sx2}{}{}{}{Linear Independence} \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx2.SS0.SSS0.Px1}{}{}{}{Question:}Consider the set % of vectors $S=\left\{\vec{0},\vec{v}_{2},\dots,\vec{v}_{k}ight\}$. Is $S$ % independent or dependent? To answer this, we must ask whether the following % homogeneous equation has a non-zero solution: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle c_{1}\vec{0}+c_{2}\vec{v}_{2}+\dots+c_{k}\vec{v}_{k}% $&$\displaystyle=\vec{0}$ Consider for instance the solution $c_{1}=3$, $c_{2},c_{3},\dots,c_{k}=0$. % This is a non-zero or non-trivial solution, hence $S$ must be dependent. \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx2.SS0.SSS0.Px2}{}{}{}{Question:}Let $S=\left\{% \vec{v}_{1},\vec{v}_{2},\vec{v}_{3}ight\}$. Suppose none of the vectors in $S$ are zero vectors, and each is perpendicular% to one another. That is, \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\vec{v}_{i}
eq\vec{0}$&$$&$\displaystyle\vec{v}_{i}% \perp\vec{v}_{j}\quad	ext{for all $i
eq j$}$ Is $S$ independent or dependent? Before we answer this question, we should % observe some noteworthy aspects of this question and how it is posed. If we % can find some useful relationships between orthogonality and linear dependence% , we will perhaps uncover illuminating geometric relationships. \par To answer the question at hand, we can start with the equation we % already know: the linear combination of vectors that equals the zero vector: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle c_{1}\vec{v}_{1}+c_{2}\vec{v}_{2}+c_{3}\vec{v}_{3}$&% $\displaystyle=\vec{0}$ it is initially unclear how the orthogonality will come into play, but % consider taking the dot product of both sides of the equation with $\vec{v}_{1% }$: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left(c_{1}\vec{v}_{1}+c_{2}\vec{v}_{2}+c_{3}\vec{v}_% {3}ight)\cdot\vec{v}_{1}$&$\displaystyle=\vec{0}\cdot\vec{v}_{1}$\ $\displaystyle c_{1}\left(\vec{v}_{1}\cdot\vec{v}_{1}ight)+c_{2}\left(\vec{v% }_{2}\cdot\vec{v}_{1}ight)+c_{3}\left(\vec{v}_{3}\cdot\vec{v}_{1}ight)$&$% \displaystyle=0$&$\displaystyle	ext{Distributive property of dot product}$\ $\displaystyle c_{1}||\vec{v}_{1}||^{2}+c_{2}(0)+c_{3}(0)$&$\displaystyle=0$&$% \displaystyle	ext{The vectors are orthogonal to each other}$\ $\displaystyle c_{1}||\vec{v}_{1}||^{2}$&$\displaystyle=0$ Since $\vec{v}_{1}
eq\vec{0}$, we know that $||\vec{v}_{1}||^{2}
eq 0$. Thus% from the above, $c_{1}=0$. \par Likewise, we find that $c_{2}=c_{3}=0$ by taking the dot product with $% \vec{v}_{2}$ and $\vec{v}_{3}$. \par Therefore, the only solution is the zero solution. Thus $S$ must be % independent. \par {Note:} In an $n$-dimensional space we cannot have more than $n$ (non-% zero) orthogonal vectors. \par \@@section{section}{Sx3}{}{}{}{Matrices} We have already seen some examples of matrices as means of storing systems of % linear equations. They are simply arrays of numbers laid out in a way in which% each entry has a convenient address. {\Large\@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}= egin{bmatrix}a_{1,1}&a_{1,2}&a_{1% ,3}\ a_{2,1}&a_{2,2}&a_{2,3}\end{bmatrix}\qquad\mathbf{A}_{2	imes 3}$ } The $i-j^{	ext{th}}$ entry is the entry found in row $i$ and column $j$. We % always give the address of the entry row first and column second \par Every matrix is described by its entries, and we sometimes write it like% below: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}=\Big(a_{ij}\Big)\qquad a_{ij}\in bR, bC$ For our purposes, the entries will almost always be from $ bR$ and $ bC$, % but keep in mind that the entries could be any object. \par It is also important to note the size of a matrix, and we often do this % by saying that $\mathbf{A}$ is an $n	imes m$ matrix, or writing $\mathbf{A}_{% n	imes m}$. \@@section{subsection}{Sx3.SSx1}{}{}{}{Algebra of Matrices} Suppose $\mathbf{A}_{m	imes n}$ and $\mathbf{B}_{m	imes n}$ are matrices of % the same size. We define several operations on matrices as follows:  egin{table}[H] \centering egin{tabular}[]{c | >{$}r<{$}@{$\,=\,$} >{$}l<{$} >{$}c<{$}}% Operation&\omit\span\omit	ext{Definition by Entry}&	ext{Resultant Size}\ \hline\hline Matrix addition&\mathbf{A} + \mathbf{B}$\,=\,$&\Big( a_{ij} + b_{% ij} \Big)&m 	imes n\ Matrix subtraction&\mathbf{A} - \mathbf{B}$\,=\,$&\Big( a_{ij} - b_{ij} \Big)&% m 	imes n\ Scalar multiplication&c \mathbf{A}$\,=\,$&\Big( c \, a_{ij} \Big) \qquad	ext{% $c$ is a scalar}&m 	imes n\end{tabular} \@add@centering\end{table} \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx3.SSx1.SSS0.Px1}{}{}{}{Example.} \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}= egin{bmatrix}[rrr]1&2&3\ 0&1&-5\end{bmatrix}$&$$&$\displaystyle\mathbf{B}= egin{bmatrix}[rrr]5&6&-6\ 0&0&3\end{bmatrix}$&$$&$\displaystyle\mathbf{C}= egin{bmatrix}[rrr]1&2\ 3&0\end{bmatrix}$ Then $\mathbf{A}+5\mathbf{B}$ is given by \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}+5\mathbf{B}= egin{bmatrix}[rrr]1&2&3\ 0&1&-5\end{bmatrix}+ egin{bmatrix}[rrr]25&30&-30\ 0&0&15\end{bmatrix}= egin{bmatrix}[rrr]26&32&-27\ 0&1&10\end{bmatrix}$ \par Some may wonder what the result of an addition such as $\mathbf{A}+% \mathbf{C}$ would be. Since the dimensions of these matrices do not match, % such an addition is not defined. It is common to wonder whether we could just % add a column of zeros to the matrix $\mathbf{C}$ in order to make the % operation defined. The response to this is that of course we could do that, % but it would completely change the matrix $\mathbf{C}$, so we do not allow % this type of operation. \par These are the simplest types of operations we can define on matrices. % Two elementary operations remain: multiplication and division. We might also % wonder about operations such as logarithm and exponentiation. We will get to % those types of operations later. \par \@@section{subsection}{Sx3.SSx2}{}{}{}{Matrix Multiplication} Matrix multiplication at first seems very strange. If we consider trying to % define a multiplication on two matrices, we might conclude from seeing % addition and subtraction that to multiply matrices they should be the same % size. In fact this is not the case. \par Before we discuss the full definition of matrix multiplication, consider% the dot product: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle egin{bmatrix}1&2&3\end{bmatrix}\cdot egin{bmatrix}% a\ b\ c\end{bmatrix}=a+2b+3c$ If the vectors had an unequal number of components then the dot product would % not be defined. If we consider the scalar $a+2b+3c$ to be the sole entry in a % matrix of size $1	imes 1$, then this tells us one possible set of sizes for % which matrix multiplication is defined: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\underbrace{ egin{bmatrix}1&2&3\end{bmatrix}}_{1% 	imes 3}\underbrace{ egin{bmatrix}a\ b\ c\end{bmatrix}}_{3	imes 1}=\underbrace{ egin{bmatrix}a+2b+3c\end{bmatrix}}_{% 1	imes 1}$ The dimensions of matrices that can be multiplied can be summarized as {\Large\@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}_{m	imes n}\,\mathbf{B}_{n	imes p}% =\mathbf{C}_{m	imes p}$ } \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx3.SSx2.SSS0.Px1}{}{}{}{Example.} \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}_{2	imes 3}= egin{bmatrix}1&2&3\ -1&4&0\end{bmatrix}$&$$&$\displaystyle\mathbf{B}_{3	imes 1}= egin{bmatrix}p% \ q\ r\end{bmatrix}$ Consider the product \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}$&$\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}1% &2&3\ -1&4&0\end{bmatrix} egin{bmatrix}p\ q\ r\end{bmatrix}$ We can evaluate this by ignoring one row at a time of $\mathbf{A}$: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\left. egin{aligned}\displaystyle\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B% }&\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}1&2&3\ \end{bmatrix} egin{bmatrix}p\ q\ r\end{bmatrix}= egin{bmatrix}p+2q+3r\ \end{bmatrix}\ \displaystyle\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}&\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}\ -1&4&0\end{bmatrix} egin{bmatrix}p\ q\ r\end{bmatrix}= egin{bmatrix}\ -p+4q+0r\end{bmatrix}\end{aligned}ight\}$&$$&$\displaystyle\longrightarrow$&% $$&$\displaystyle egin{aligned}\displaystyle\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}&% \displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}1&2&3\ -1&4&0\end{bmatrix} egin{bmatrix}p\ q\ r\end{bmatrix}\ &\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}p+2q+3r\ -p+4q+0r\end{bmatrix}_{2	imes 1}\end{aligned}$ \par It may be startling to observe the outcome of trying to multiply $% \mathbf{B}$ by $\mathbf{A}$: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{B}_{3	imes 1}\mathbf{A}_{2	imes 3}$&$% \displaystyle=	ext{Not defined}$ Because the dimensions of the two matrices do not correctly line up in this % order, they cannot be multiplied in this way. The technical term for this is % that, in general, matrix multiplication is {non-commutative}. That is, $% \mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}
eq\mathbf{B}\mathbf{A}$. In fact, both need not be % defined at all, depending on their sizes. \par \@@section{subsection}{Sx3.SSx3}{}{}{}{Another Perspective on Matrix % Multiplication} Consider again the matrix multiplication from the previous example. We can % view this multiplication in a number of ways: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}$&$\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}1% &2&3\ -1&4&0\end{bmatrix} egin{bmatrix}p\ q\ r\end{bmatrix}$\ $$&$\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}p+2q+3r\ -p+4q+0r\end{bmatrix}$&$$&$\displaystyle\Longleftarrow	ext{Each row is a % linear combination of rows of $\mathbf{B}$}$\ $$&$\displaystyle=p egin{bmatrix}1\ -1\end{bmatrix}+q egin{bmatrix}2\ 4\end{bmatrix}+r egin{bmatrix}3\ 0\end{bmatrix}$&$$&$\displaystyle\Longleftarrow	ext{Linear combination of the% columns of $\mathbf{A}$}$ The three ways of viewing matrix multiplication are  egin{enumerate} \enumerate@item{ \@@amsalign$\displaystyle c_{ij}= egin{pmatrix}\leftarrow	ext{row $i$ of $% \mathbf{A}$}ightarrow\end{pmatrix} egin{pmatrix}\uparrow\ 	ext{col. $j$}\ 	ext{of $\mathbf{B}$}\ \downarrow\end{pmatrix}$ } \enumerate@item{ $i^{	ext{th}}$ row of $\mathbf{C}$ is a linear combination of rows of $% \mathbf{B}$ with coefficients from the $i^{	ext{th}}$ row of $\mathbf{A}$. } \enumerate@item{ $j^{	ext{th}}$ column of $\mathbf{C}$ is a linear combination of columns of $% \mathbf{A}$ with coefficients from the $j^{	ext{th}}$ column of $\mathbf{B}$. } \end{enumerate} \par \@@section{paragraph}{Sx3.SSx3.SSS0.Px1}{}{}{}{Example.} We will try % multiplication with each of the three ways of viewing matrix multiplication. \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{A}= egin{bmatrix}1&2\ 0&1\end{bmatrix}$&$$&$\displaystyle\mathbf{B}= egin{bmatrix}1&2\ 0&0\ -1&12\end{bmatrix}$ Note that $\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}$ is not defined, but $\mathbf{B}\mathbf{A}$ is% defined. Let $\mathbf{C}=\mathbf{B}\mathbf{A}$, the matrix whose entries we % will try to find. \par  egin{enumerate} \enumerate@item{ First method: \par \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{C}= egin{bmatrix}c_{11}&c_{12}\ c_{21}&c_{22}\ c_{31}&c_{32}\end{bmatrix}_{3	imes 2}$ \@@amsalign$\displaystyle c_{11}$&$\displaystyle=\overbrace{ egin{pmatrix}1&2% \end{pmatrix}}^{	ext{Row $1$ of $\mathbf{B}$}}\cdot\underbrace{ egin{pmatrix% }1\ 0\end{pmatrix}}_{\mathclap{	ext{Column $1$ of $\mathbf{A}$}}}=1$ Similarly, \@@amsalign$\displaystyle c_{32}$&$\displaystyle= egin{pmatrix}-1&12\end{% pmatrix}\cdot egin{pmatrix}2\ 1\end{pmatrix}=10$ So \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{C}= egin{bmatrix}1&c_{12}\ c_{21}&c_{22}\ c_{31}&10\end{bmatrix}_{3	imes 2}$ \par } \enumerate@item{ Next, we will use the second method. This says that rows of $\mathbf{C}$ are % linear combinations of rows of $\mathbf{A}$. \@@amsalign$\displaystyle	ext{Row 1}$&$\displaystyle=1 egin{bmatrix}1&2\end{% bmatrix}+2 egin{bmatrix}0&1\end{bmatrix}$ The coefficients $1$ and $2$ in front of the rows of $\mathbf{A}$ are taken % from the first row of $\mathbf{B}$. \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{C}= egin{bmatrix}1&4\ c_{21}&c_{22}\ c_{31}&10\end{bmatrix}_{3	imes 2}$ } \enumerate@item{ The next method states that columns of $\mathbf{C}$ are linear combinations of% columns of $\mathbf{B}$. \@@amsalign$\displaystyle	ext{Column 2}$&$\displaystyle=2 egin{bmatrix}1\ 0\ -1\end{bmatrix}+1 egin{bmatrix}2\ 0\ 12\end{bmatrix}$\ $$&$\displaystyle= egin{bmatrix}4\ 0\ 10\end{bmatrix}$ This allows us to fill in another entry of $\mathbf{C}$: \@@amsalign$\displaystyle\mathbf{C}= egin{bmatrix}1&4\ c_{21}&0\ c_{31}&10\end{bmatrix}_{3	imes 2}$ } \end{enumerate} \par \end{document}
